---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro'
import Hero from '../../components/Hero.astro'

const heroProps = {
  title: 'Case Study',
  subtitle: 'Changing Sedentary Habits Through Behavioral UX Design',
}
---

<Layout
  title="zntlDesk Case Study"
  description="How behavioral UX design, gamification, and automatic detection can change sedentary habits at standing desks. A deep dive into the zntlDesk project."
>
  <Hero {...heroProps} />
  <section class="section-full">
    <div class="container-padded">
      <article class="prose prose-blog mx-auto max-w-4xl">
        <div class="mb-12 flex flex-wrap gap-3">
          <span
            class="rounded-full border border-gray-700 px-3 py-1 text-sm text-gray-300"
            >Behavioral UX</span
          >
          <span
            class="rounded-full border border-gray-700 px-3 py-1 text-sm text-gray-300"
            >IoT / Hardware</span
          >
          <span
            class="rounded-full border border-gray-700 px-3 py-1 text-sm text-gray-300"
            >Rust + React</span
          >
          <span
            class="rounded-full border border-gray-700 px-3 py-1 text-sm text-gray-300"
            >Gamification</span
          >
          <span
            class="rounded-full border border-gray-700 px-3 py-1 text-sm text-gray-300"
            >Open Source</span
          >
        </div>

        <!-- ===== THE PROBLEM ===== -->
        <h2>The Problem</h2>

        <p>
          Standing desks are everywhere. They are in offices, home setups, and
          coworking spaces. Yet the data tells a different story: the average
          standing desk owner stands for less than 15% of their workday. The desk
          goes up once in the morning, comes back down, and stays there.
        </p>

        <p>
          This is the <strong>behavior gap</strong> — the distance between owning
          a tool and actually using it. Standing desks are sold as health
          solutions, but they are really just furniture. Without behavioral
          intervention, nothing changes.
        </p>

        <blockquote>
          The problem is not that people lack a standing desk. The problem is
          that nothing tells them when to use it.
        </blockquote>

        <!-- Placeholder: illustration of behavior gap -->
        <div
          class="my-10 flex h-48 items-center justify-center rounded-lg border border-dashed border-gray-700 bg-gray-900/30"
        >
          <span class="text-sm text-gray-500"
            >[Image: The Behavior Gap — ownership vs. usage over time]</span
          >
        </div>

        <!-- ===== MY APPROACH ===== -->
        <h2>My Approach</h2>

        <p>
          I started from the hypothesis that the problem is not awareness — it is
          friction. People know they should stand more. They just do not act on
          it because nothing in their environment prompts the change at the right
          moment.
        </p>

        <p>The design principles that emerged:</p>

        <ul>
          <li>
            <strong>Automatic detection, not manual tracking.</strong> A ToF laser
            sensor mounted under the desk detects height changes instantly. The user
            never logs anything.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Coach, not tracker.</strong> The app does not just show data —
            it tells you <em>when</em> to change position, with escalating urgency.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Gamification with real consequences.</strong> Negative scores
            are valid gameplay. If you ignore prompts, your score drops. Comeback
            mechanics make recovery feel rewarding, not punishing.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Progressive escalation.</strong> Gentle visual cues first, then
            stronger nudges, then direct notifications. The system never starts by
            shouting.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Position changes over standing duration.</strong> The goal is
            not to stand for hours — it is to change positions frequently. Two
            minutes of standing counts as a valid position change. The metric that
            matters is transitions per day, not total standing time.
          </li>
        </ul>

        <!-- ===== THE SOLUTION ===== -->
        <h2>The Solution: zntlDesk</h2>

        <p>
          zntlDesk is an open source desktop application built with Tauri (Rust
          backend + React frontend). It pairs with a VL53L1X Time-of-Flight
          sensor on an ESP32-C3 microcontroller to automatically detect desk
          height and user posture.
        </p>

        <div class="my-10 grid grid-cols-1 gap-6 md:grid-cols-2">
          <div class="rounded-lg border border-gray-800 bg-gray-900/40 p-6">
            <h5>Hardware</h5>
            <ul class="mt-2">
              <li>VL53L1X ToF sensor (Class 1 eye-safe)</li>
              <li>Seeed XIAO ESP32-C3 MCU</li>
              <li>USB connection (no wireless complexity)</li>
              <li>Under-desk mount, pointing to floor</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="rounded-lg border border-gray-800 bg-gray-900/40 p-6">
            <h5>Software</h5>
            <ul class="mt-2">
              <li>Rust backend (Tauri 2) with native WinAPI overlay</li>
              <li>React + TypeScript frontend</li>
              <li>SQLite persistence via tauri-plugin-sql</li>
              <li>Remote phone dashboard via WebSocket</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Placeholder: screenshot of the app -->
        <div
          class="my-10 flex h-64 items-center justify-center rounded-lg border border-dashed border-gray-700 bg-gray-900/30"
        >
          <span class="text-sm text-gray-500"
            >[Screenshot: zntlDesk floating window with KPI dashboard and
            session history]</span
          >
        </div>

        <!-- ===== RESULTS ===== -->
        <h2>Results</h2>

        <p class="text-sm uppercase tracking-wide text-gray-400">
          Placeholder data — real metrics collection in progress
        </p>

        <div class="my-10 grid grid-cols-1 gap-6 md:grid-cols-3">
          <div
            class="rounded-lg border border-gray-800 bg-gray-900/40 p-6 text-center"
          >
            <p class="mb-1 text-sm text-gray-400">Standing time / day</p>
            <p class="text-3xl font-light text-white">
              8% <span class="text-green-400">&rarr;</span> 22%
            </p>
          </div>
          <div
            class="rounded-lg border border-gray-800 bg-gray-900/40 p-6 text-center"
          >
            <p class="mb-1 text-sm text-gray-400">Position changes / day</p>
            <p class="text-3xl font-light text-white">
              1.2 <span class="text-green-400">&rarr;</span> 4.8
            </p>
          </div>
          <div
            class="rounded-lg border border-gray-800 bg-gray-900/40 p-6 text-center"
          >
            <p class="mb-1 text-sm text-gray-400">Longest sitting session</p>
            <p class="text-3xl font-light text-white">
              3.5h <span class="text-green-400">&rarr;</span> 52min
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- ===== KEY UX INNOVATIONS ===== -->
        <h2>Key UX Innovations</h2>

        <h4>Overlay progress bar</h4>
        <p>
          A 4-pixel bar at the very top of the screen, rendered via native
          WinAPI (not a web layer). It transitions from green through yellow to
          red as a sitting session progresses. It is always visible but never
          intrusive — peripheral vision registers the color shift without
          conscious attention.
        </p>

        <!-- Placeholder: overlay bar screenshot -->
        <div
          class="my-10 flex h-24 items-center justify-center rounded-lg border border-dashed border-gray-700 bg-gray-900/30"
        >
          <span class="text-sm text-gray-500"
            >[Screenshot: Overlay progress bar at different stages — green,
            yellow, red]</span
          >
        </div>

        <h4>Coach messaging with comeback mechanics</h4>
        <p>
          The system speaks like a coach, not a dashboard. When you ignore
          alerts, your score drops — but when you finally stand up, the
          comeback message acknowledges the recovery. Negative score is valid
          gameplay: it creates tension that makes the comeback satisfying.
        </p>

        <h4>Widget temperature system</h4>
        <p>
          Visual urgency is communicated through color temperature across all UI
          elements simultaneously — tray icon, overlay bar, popup progress, and
          KPI badges all shift in sync. No text needed. The entire interface
          "heats up" as you sit longer.
        </p>

        <h4>Position changes as the core metric</h4>
        <p>
          Most standing desk trackers optimize for standing duration. zntlDesk
          optimizes for <em>transitions</em>. A 5-minute standing break is worth
          more than a 2-hour standing marathon. This aligns with ergonomic
          research: frequent changes matter more than total time in any single
          position.
        </p>

        <!-- ===== TECHNICAL DEPTH ===== -->
        <h2>Technical Depth</h2>

        <div class="my-10 grid grid-cols-1 gap-6 md:grid-cols-2">
          <div class="rounded-lg border border-gray-800 bg-gray-900/40 p-6">
            <h5>Test coverage</h5>
            <p class="mt-2 text-base text-gray-300">
              356 Rust unit tests cover the session state machine, overlay
              rendering logic, break credit calculations, alert firing rules,
              and height calibration. 189 TypeScript tests cover React
              components, hooks, and utilities. Integration tests simulate
              full sensor-to-UI flows.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="rounded-lg border border-gray-800 bg-gray-900/40 p-6">
            <h5>Native overlay renderer</h5>
            <p class="mt-2 text-base text-gray-300">
              The progress bar is a native WinAPI window — not Electron, not a
              WebView. It uses GDI rendering with
              <code>UpdateLayeredWindow</code> for transparency. This keeps
              memory under 250 MB and avoids the overhead of a second browser
              process.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="rounded-lg border border-gray-800 bg-gray-900/40 p-6">
            <h5>Modular alert state machine</h5>
            <p class="mt-2 text-base text-gray-300">
              AlertManager is a pure function: current state in, list of
              actions out. No side effects, no timers, no UI coupling. The
              tray controller executes the actions. This makes the escalation
              logic fully testable and easy to reconfigure.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="rounded-lg border border-gray-800 bg-gray-900/40 p-6">
            <h5>Open core model</h5>
            <p class="mt-2 text-base text-gray-300">
              The desktop app is open source (MIT/Apache). Cloud sync, AI
              coaching, and smartwatch integration are closed/paid features.
              This lets developers build on the platform while sustaining
              development through SaaS revenue.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

